The issue seems to be with the file `c-blosc/blosc/blosc.c` and the following definition block:

```
#if defined(_WIN32)
  #include "win32/pthread.h"
  #include "win32/pthread.c"
#else
  #include <pthread.h>
#endif
```
Replacing the entire block by the non-win32 definition `#include <pthread.h>` allows building the package. It seem the win32 already provides the functions that are provided by `win32/pthread.c`.

@troydai I don't really have an issue with message.  It looks like this is a case where the server is returning a junk error message, just like here: https://github.com/Azure/azure-storage-python/issues/181

I'm fine with the workaround so our customers don't suffer, but we should create a tracking issue either in our repo with the ServiceAttn label or in the Python SDK repo (where they will give it the ServerIssue label) and comment the workaround with this issue so that when it is resolved, we can remove it.

Right now, if the service started supporting more than 5 CORS rules, we're making bad assumptions.

